I&#39;ve managed to implement solution through `OperationMap`

    type OperationMap&lt;T&gt; = 
        T extends Date
            ? (DateFilterOp | FilterOp)
            : T extends Array&lt;any&gt;
                ? ArrayFilterOp
                : T extends String
                    ? FilterOp | StringFilterOp
        : FilterOp;
    
    type GenericFilter&lt;T&gt; = {
        Property: string,
        Value: T,
        Operation: OperationMap&lt;T&gt;
    }

Assuming I understand the constraint correctly, you could use [conditional types](https://github.com/Microsoft/TypeScript/wiki/What&#39;s-new-in-TypeScript#conditional-types) to represent it:

    type Operation&lt;T&gt; =
      | FilterOp
      | (T extends Array&lt;any&gt; ? ArrayFilterOp : never)
      | (T extends string ? StringFilterOp : never)
      | (T extends Date ? DateFilterOp : never);
    
    type GenericFilter&lt;T&gt; = {
      Property: string;
      Value: T;
      Operation: Operation&lt;T&gt;;
    };
    
This will support your stated use case:

    let dateFilter: GenericFilter&lt;Date&gt; = {
      Property: &quot;DateCreated&quot;,
      Value: new Date(),
      Operation: &quot;DateIn&quot;
    };

as well as work with a helper function so you can just *infer* `T` instead of specifying it manually:
    
    const asGenericFilter = &lt;T&gt;(filt: GenericFilter&lt;T&gt;) =&gt; filt;
    
    let stringFilter = asGenericFilter({
      Property: &quot;Name&quot;,
      Value: &quot;Alice&quot;,
      Operation: &quot;StartsWith&quot; // hinted as Operation&lt;string&gt;
    })

Hope that helps; good luck!

